A question which has been much discussed is why Possession‚ apart from bona fides and title, came to be treated as a right, and protected by legal remedies. To this Savigny answers, that the violation ol Possession‚ being in itsell no wrong, can originally have been re· dressed only because it went hand in hand with some violation oi an actual right, and that lull justice could not have been done in the matter ol this latter violation, unless· at the same time the Possession were protected. All the possessory interdicts, he says, presuppose some wronglul act. In cases of violent dispossession this is obvious ; but even where there is no violence the idea is the same3 e. g. in the application oi the interdict de precario there is the wrongful act ol abusing another person's good nature: cl. Holland’s Jurisprudence, p. ¹30· On the historical question, in what connection the necessity of legal protection was first selt, Savigny adopts the theory ol Niebuhr, that possessory interdicte were originally devised in order to guard the interest os the individual citizen in the ager publicus, which the State permitted him to occupy and enjoy, and were subsequently extended to the Possession ol private property, moveable and im· moveable.
